# NestJS Architecture & Decoupling

## Rule
Business logic, ledger mutations, and financial orchestration must never be coupled directly within `Controllers` or GraphQL `Resolvers`.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Controllers/Resolvers are restricted exclusively to:
  - Request routing (`@Get`, `@Post`, `@Mutation`, `@Query`, etc.)
  - Input schema validation via NestJS `ValidationPipe` + `class-validator` DTOs
  - Response transformation/shaping (mapping service results to response DTOs)
- All transactional logic, escrow processing, rate calculations, and any state mutation must reside in specialized, injectable `Services`.
- A Controller/Resolver method body should read as a thin orchestration of: validate input → call one (or few) service method(s) → map/return result. No direct database client calls, no raw business rule branching (e.g. fee calculation, escrow state machine logic) inline in the handler.

## What to flag in review
- Any `PrismaService`, `DataSource`, or raw repository call made directly inside a `*.controller.ts` or `*.resolver.ts` file.
- Conditional business rules (e.g. `if (amount > limit) { ... }`, fee/rate math, escrow status transitions) written inline in a handler instead of delegated to a service method.
- Controllers/Resolvers exceeding a few lines per handler, or importing domain entities/ledger types directly instead of going through a service-layer DTO/result type.
- Missing or bypassed `ValidationPipe`/DTO on inputs that are passed straight into a service call.

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ Bad — business logic inside the controller
@Post('transfer')
async transfer(@Body() body: any) {
  const account = await this.prisma.account.findUnique({ where: { id: body.fromId } });
  if (account.balance < body.amount) {
    throw new Error('not enough funds');
  }
  // ... inline ledger mutation
}

// ✅ Good — controller delegates to service
@Post('transfer')
async transfer(@Body() dto: TransferDto): Promise<TransferResponseDto> {
  return this.transactionsService.transfer(dto);
}
```
